1
00:00:04,503 --> 00:00:09,326
So I want to continue saying something about the first noble truth, the truth of dukkha.

2
00:00:10,888 --> 00:00:12,971
So there is what's described as dukkha dukkha.

3
00:00:12,990 --> 00:00:21,698
That's the real suffering that we'd all agree is suffering of pain, illness, disability, death, loss of loved ones and so on.

4
00:00:22,458 --> 00:00:25,542
Things that genuinely we all sympathise with each other for.

5
00:00:27,143 --> 00:00:34,509
And then there was what I was talking about this morning, anicca dukkha, the suffering, the dissatisfaction associated with the fact that things change.

6
00:00:35,840 --> 00:00:38,482
that we can't hold on forever to our happiness.

7
00:00:40,185 --> 00:00:44,591
And then very much related to it is what I want to talk about tonight, anatta dukkha.

8
00:00:45,252 --> 00:00:48,195
And anatta is usually translated as not-self.

9
00:00:49,616 --> 00:00:55,524
Now, it's a very confusing area of Buddhist thought.

10
00:00:56,746 --> 00:00:59,789
So if you get confused tonight, just know you're in good company.

11
00:00:59,990 --> 00:01:02,353
It's easy, easy to get confused.

12
00:01:05,269 --> 00:01:14,543
So, of course, it's confusing in the sense that, you know, it's obvious to us, you could say that I am me and you're you and, you know, everybody is themselves.

13
00:01:15,022 --> 00:01:17,387
So what on earth do we mean by not self?

14
00:01:19,289 --> 00:01:23,355
We, you know, we see ourselves as separate parcels of existence.

15
00:01:25,096 --> 00:01:29,302
And the Buddha would agree that for practical purposes, yes, that this is true.

16
00:01:30,667 --> 00:01:35,733
But it's not true all the time that there are times when our sense of self can just drop away.

17
00:01:35,774 --> 00:01:39,881
So the normal view is true too.

18
00:01:39,980 --> 00:01:41,903
We can operate in the world as a self.

19
00:01:41,944 --> 00:01:44,367
We can decide to do certain things.

20
00:01:46,090 --> 00:01:55,222
But at another level, an ultimate level, we can let our sense of self drop away and experience a peace, the peace of anata, the peace of not-self.

21
00:01:58,021 --> 00:02:09,498
So the truth of annata is really saying that we don't have a totally separate identity, that we are interdependent, very, very, very intimately interdependent.

22
00:02:10,621 --> 00:02:25,024
And just one experience, my first experience or inkling of this was one time I was hearing a bird song and hearing, hearing, and I was really liking the bird song and then

23
00:02:25,460 --> 00:02:27,682
When the bird stopped, I noticed I got anxious.

24
00:02:28,104 --> 00:02:30,086
Then the bird would start again and I'd be delighted.

25
00:02:30,145 --> 00:02:32,188
Stop, I get anxious and so on.

26
00:02:33,030 --> 00:02:37,977
So it came to me, you know, just that direct contact with the sound.

27
00:02:38,576 --> 00:02:42,042
It seemed to me, well, is that sound inside me or outside of me?

28
00:02:43,163 --> 00:02:44,224
And I couldn't really tell.

29
00:02:44,245 --> 00:02:49,372
You know, I mean, I knew at the conceptual level that the bird was outside.

30
00:02:49,431 --> 00:02:53,997
But at another level, you know, my ears were hearing the sound directly.

31
00:02:54,349 --> 00:02:56,431
My brain, I suppose, was processing it.

32
00:02:57,252 --> 00:03:07,545
And all the neurons and the hormones required to make me feel anxious or happy were happening within me as a result of that sound.

33
00:03:08,366 --> 00:03:15,514
So it just seemed that direct interconnection between the bird and me, that the bird was pushing all my buttons at that time.

34
00:03:15,534 --> 00:03:18,057
The bird was more in control of me than I was, you know.

35
00:03:18,498 --> 00:03:22,804
He could decide whether to stop or start singing and then I'd have to go anxious or happy.

36
00:03:24,455 --> 00:03:30,201
That's just an example of that truth of interdependence, anatta, that we're not separate.

37
00:03:30,643 --> 00:03:37,632
You know, at that moment, because I was just directly hearing, I had no real sense of a boundary between myself and the bird.

38
00:03:39,193 --> 00:03:43,519
Because I wasn't thinking me, bird, I was just hearing and feeling the response.

39
00:03:45,161 --> 00:03:51,930
So that for me was kind of a level of insight anyway into this truth of anatta.

40
00:03:52,939 --> 00:04:07,338
And it kind of was scary in some sense, because I just realized how incredibly vulnerable we are, you know, that we're so open to our emotional openness to each other is, you know, it's very deep.

41
00:04:08,080 --> 00:04:18,153
But it also struck me as very beautiful, you know, that for at least that moment, I could see that I wasn't actually separate from the rest of the universe, not in an essential way, a permanent way.

42
00:04:21,576 --> 00:04:29,310
Now, at some level, we know this because we know that our feelings and emotions are all triggered by each other.

43
00:04:29,350 --> 00:04:32,435
You know, people can push our buttons and we get annoyed or whatever.

44
00:04:32,475 --> 00:04:37,163
So we know we're not separate in that sense, that we directly affect each other.

45
00:04:38,303 --> 00:04:43,533
But I think we can experience it at a deeper level if we really, really pay attention.

46
00:04:44,093 --> 00:04:47,819
Feeling that direct contact with the world, direct contact with our emotions,

47
00:04:48,172 --> 00:04:56,158
That sense of a separate boundary of me and the world just starts to get fuzzy, very fuzzy and unclear.

48
00:04:56,199 --> 00:05:02,225
And in reality, then, you know, we're very deeply interdependent.

49
00:05:02,245 --> 00:05:04,286
We're actually kind of co-creating each other.

50
00:05:04,987 --> 00:05:14,976
You know, even what's happening here now, I'm speaking and you're hearing and, you know, by you listening, I'm having to process ideas.

51
00:05:14,997 --> 00:05:18,060
So we're all changing at the moment very deeply.

52
00:05:18,444 --> 00:05:23,629
And yeah, we're co-creating each other and our own reality.

53
00:05:25,490 --> 00:05:29,574
So I think it's an idea worth dwelling on that the level of interdependence.

54
00:05:32,257 --> 00:05:38,583
But as opposed to that, that there's also a strong sense of identity, you know, me, mine, my biscuit.

55
00:05:40,343 --> 00:05:47,810
And so there is a sense of a big boundary around me now.

56
00:05:49,411 --> 00:05:53,137
The Buddha would say, this is really, it's a belief.

57
00:05:53,858 --> 00:05:57,084
The belief that I am a separate parcel of existence.

58
00:05:57,966 --> 00:05:59,009
It's a very strong belief.

59
00:06:00,752 --> 00:06:02,194
But it can come and go.

60
00:06:02,214 --> 00:06:04,257
It can come and go.

61
00:06:04,278 --> 00:06:07,824
It's created in order to fulfill a desire.

62
00:06:09,468 --> 00:06:11,672
So, it's

63
00:06:12,209 --> 00:06:23,206
It's probably evolutionary in nature in the sense that we have to, you know, fight or fly from a tiger, you know, in order to survive as an animal in this world.

64
00:06:24,007 --> 00:06:31,980
So a sense of self that I'm important, my life is important and I have to get away from this threat is really important for survival.

65
00:06:32,862 --> 00:06:37,069
And similarly, I have to eat all this lovely food because again, I'm important.

66
00:06:37,706 --> 00:06:42,654
So that sense of self that gets created is very possibly evolutionary.

67
00:06:43,435 --> 00:06:47,000
And it helps us enormously in life.

68
00:06:47,562 --> 00:06:51,608
It's not to think of the sense of self as wrong, but it's just it's not ultimate.

69
00:06:51,908 --> 00:06:53,211
It's not the absolute truth.

70
00:06:53,331 --> 00:06:57,117
It's not the forever and ever truth that we have to experience all the time.

71
00:06:59,543 --> 00:07:06,529
So it's basically a construction in the mind that happens once we feel a desire.

72
00:07:06,550 --> 00:07:17,521
You know, if we're walking along the street and we pass by a cafe and we get the aroma of coffee and we look in the window and we see luscious cream cakes, then suddenly the desire arises for coffee and cake.

73
00:07:18,461 --> 00:07:22,485
And we immediately turn and go in and, you know, get the coffee and cake.

74
00:07:23,107 --> 00:07:28,031
So the sense of self was just constructed there in order to fulfill that desire.

75
00:07:33,057 --> 00:07:48,011
Now, I think it's interesting that one teacher says, and I can't remember the name, unfortunately, but anyway, he would say that the mind state, the sense of not-self, is actually much more common.

76
00:07:48,031 --> 00:07:50,632
But it's just that it's so unobtrusive that we don't notice it.

77
00:07:50,932 --> 00:07:53,415
It's happening most of the time, all our lives.

78
00:07:54,076 --> 00:07:55,978
But we just don't notice it.

79
00:07:57,899 --> 00:08:01,343
It's just that when an idea isn't in our mind, we don't think about it.

80
00:08:01,524 --> 00:08:12,697
So, for example, the usual example that's given, I think, is if I tell you, don't think about a pink elephant, most people just start immediately thinking about a pink elephant, you know?

81
00:08:13,877 --> 00:08:20,985
And it's the same way if I say, well, don't think about yourself, you know, just drop that idea, you immediately start thinking about yourself.

82
00:08:21,586 --> 00:08:22,588
You know, of course I'm me.

83
00:08:22,827 --> 00:08:29,295
So there's, we can't stop thinking, we can't stop thinking about an idea on willpower, you know?

84
00:08:29,314 --> 00:08:31,396
The idea stimulates the idea.

85
00:08:32,575 --> 00:08:35,359
So it's the very same for the sense of self.

86
00:08:36,100 --> 00:08:41,166
When it's there, when the idea of self is there, it's strong, it's very persuasive.

87
00:08:42,028 --> 00:08:48,316
It really tells us that we are an important person who needs this, that and the other thing.

88
00:08:48,576 --> 00:08:58,009
And when it just falls away, as it does when there's just no desire happening, just peaceful moments in life, it's such...

89
00:08:58,477 --> 00:09:05,166
a simple, unobtrusive, not demanding attention type of mind state to be in, that we just don't notice it.

90
00:09:06,767 --> 00:09:13,855
So in that sense we often don't experience that truth of an atta, but in actual fact it's there in the background of our lives all the time.

91
00:09:15,758 --> 00:09:22,684
Now one mistake we can make around all this is to think we're bad for having a sense of self.

92
00:09:24,246 --> 00:09:28,451
We hear the teaching that not-self is

93
00:09:29,326 --> 00:09:35,092
a deep truth, a very peaceful truth, and we want to be in that state all of the time.

94
00:09:35,133 --> 00:09:38,136
Now, that's an impossibility.

95
00:09:38,197 --> 00:09:41,020
This is a gradual path.

96
00:09:41,421 --> 00:09:53,515
The Buddha often described his path to full enlightenment as a very gradual path, like he likened it to the continental shelf, just gradually sloping into the ocean, gradually getting deeper and deeper.

97
00:09:55,258 --> 00:09:56,700
And the sense of self,

98
00:09:57,288 --> 00:10:04,054
is an important part of getting us to the deeper truth of not-self.

99
00:10:06,177 --> 00:10:15,264
So we need to have a strong, well-developed, confident, good, healthy sense of ourselves in order to tread the path.

100
00:10:17,206 --> 00:10:22,972
So to be thinking of ourselves as wrong is not the idea that the Buddha was trying to get across.

101
00:10:23,033 --> 00:10:24,214
In fact, he would say the opposite.

102
00:10:24,234 --> 00:10:26,316
He would often say, you know, cherish yourselves.

103
00:10:26,802 --> 00:10:32,769
Do what's best for your own happiness, which is to tread this path.

104
00:10:33,009 --> 00:10:34,871
Strive diligently for your liberation.

105
00:10:35,493 --> 00:10:43,903
So he would tell us to really look after ourselves in order to find the deeper happiness where this is the truth of Anatta.

106
00:10:48,488 --> 00:10:54,936
So the self-remember is created, you know, construction in the mind, an idea you could say that comes and goes.

107
00:10:55,490 --> 00:10:57,432
In order to fulfil a desire.

108
00:10:57,493 --> 00:10:59,596
So there can be really, really wise desires.

109
00:11:00,758 --> 00:11:08,649
The desire to meditate, the desire to come and retreat, the desire to help others, to care for others, to give service and work and so on.

110
00:11:09,289 --> 00:11:14,557
So these are all very wise desires that it's good to create a good sense of self in order to do them.

111
00:11:16,400 --> 00:11:19,546
To help our friends and to be a good friend and so on.

112
00:11:19,566 --> 00:11:22,509
These are really wise desires that help the world in the right direction.

113
00:11:23,332 --> 00:11:38,726
So we certainly do need to look after ourselves to do our best to really have a good, confident sense of self, to love ourselves, to care for ourselves and not to run ourselves down.

114
00:11:43,312 --> 00:11:46,474
So the Buddha never, never said that the sense of self was wrong.

115
00:11:46,514 --> 00:11:49,216
He would have said the opposite, you know, care for yourself.

116
00:11:49,937 --> 00:11:52,480
All he said was that it's temporary.

117
00:11:52,779 --> 00:11:53,922
It's insubstantial.

118
00:11:54,942 --> 00:11:56,684
It's a state of mind that comes and goes.

119
00:11:57,886 --> 00:11:59,448
It comes up when we have a desire.

120
00:12:00,890 --> 00:12:07,801
Once that desire has been fulfilled, it'll actually drop away again, but we just don't notice it because it's so unobtrusive.

121
00:12:14,470 --> 00:12:20,778
So basically then, our work really is to decide when to create a sense of self.

122
00:12:21,096 --> 00:12:29,610
you know, which desires to fulfill, which ones to really get ourselves together and, you know, attack with gusto and say, yes, I will do this.

123
00:12:30,471 --> 00:12:43,230
And then which desires can we let go of in order to move towards that deep peace of not-self, of not having to react to every single whim.

124
00:12:46,654 --> 00:12:49,399
Now, although it's hard to...

125
00:12:49,732 --> 00:12:57,120
experience the sense of not-self, though we might on occasion, but it is possible to tune into the experience of a self being created.

126
00:12:57,381 --> 00:13:04,269
You know, that's easier to, and it's just very interesting to see it happening, and I think you probably will start seeing it happening if you just tune in.

127
00:13:06,591 --> 00:13:15,182
Say in life, for example, if somebody gives you a compliment, then you might immediately just feel kind of, you know, yourself growing taller.

128
00:13:15,361 --> 00:13:16,803
Gregory Kramer calls it puffing up.

129
00:13:17,053 --> 00:13:21,618
The whole sense of self is fed, is nourished by getting a compliment.

130
00:13:22,239 --> 00:13:25,981
So we feel bigger, we feel stronger, we feel more confident.

131
00:13:27,462 --> 00:13:29,284
Yeah, we feel important and so on.

132
00:13:29,865 --> 00:13:31,126
So it's a good feeling.

133
00:13:31,226 --> 00:13:35,289
A very happy sense of self is created for a few moments at least when we get a compliment.

134
00:13:35,931 --> 00:13:45,019
So just tuning into that, just noticing the sense of me, me, an important person, just coming up.

135
00:13:45,927 --> 00:14:13,250
and that's all not criticizing just the wonder of it you know how the whole being can be stimulated by various things of course the opposite can happen you know we can create a very unhappy sense of self if we get for example criticized or ignored or something like that and again it's it's interesting to tune into what happens there and often

136
00:14:13,788 --> 00:14:16,130
Yeah, I experience it as some sort of a collapse.

137
00:14:17,873 --> 00:14:25,260
So even physically, you know, the head might go down, the shoulders might droop and a sense of dullness maybe comes into the mind.

138
00:14:26,062 --> 00:14:33,409
A sense of, you know, well, it could be anger, of course, but anger will probably create that sort of important sense of self.

139
00:14:33,850 --> 00:14:43,760
But if it's not anger, if it's sort of, you know, I'm no good type feeling, then that often feels like a collapse, some sort of a dulling down.

140
00:14:44,618 --> 00:14:50,605
So it's just to tune into the process of what many teachers call selfing.

141
00:14:50,645 --> 00:14:59,317
You know, it's a verb, the self getting created, a mental process happening in moment after moment so we can tune into it.

142
00:15:03,761 --> 00:15:08,128
Now it is harder to tune into the dropping away of self and

143
00:15:09,778 --> 00:15:16,745
In the same way as, you know, if you have a toothache, while it's there, it's the centre of your experience, the centre of existence.

144
00:15:16,785 --> 00:15:18,366
It's so important and it's terrible.

145
00:15:19,087 --> 00:15:22,110
But do you ever, and maybe hours later you notice, oh, it's gone.

146
00:15:23,131 --> 00:15:25,855
Or days later you might notice, oh, it's gone.

147
00:15:26,434 --> 00:15:29,197
But do you ever notice the last moment of a toothache?

148
00:15:30,678 --> 00:15:31,941
You know, very few people do.

149
00:15:33,961 --> 00:15:34,962
I don't know if I ever have.

150
00:15:35,024 --> 00:15:35,783
No, I don't think so.

151
00:15:36,865 --> 00:15:39,668
I have noticed the last moment of shorter term things like cramp

152
00:15:39,967 --> 00:15:41,809
just if you can tune into them.

153
00:15:42,230 --> 00:15:50,660
And it is very interesting just to follow them to the end and how the mind just loses interest really towards the end when the pain is going away.

154
00:15:53,484 --> 00:15:56,567
So in that sense, yeah, it's harder to notice the dropping away of self.

155
00:15:56,587 --> 00:16:08,101
We just don't notice the absence of problems usually because when the self is there, it's usually big and strong and often creating some sort of a problem because it wants to get its desires met.

156
00:16:08,351 --> 00:16:10,554
So the sense of self can often be problematic for us.

157
00:16:11,095 --> 00:16:15,981
But when it all dies away, it's like a toothache or a cramp dying away.

158
00:16:16,042 --> 00:16:19,265
It's just not terribly interesting for us.

159
00:16:19,285 --> 00:16:20,447
It doesn't call attention.

160
00:16:23,191 --> 00:16:32,722
But in meditation here, we can sometimes just dip into experiences where we are just in direct contact with reality.

161
00:16:33,293 --> 00:16:43,866
We're simply hearing or feeling our bodies, sensations, our moods, feeling all that without the added layer of concept and thought.

162
00:16:44,927 --> 00:16:51,517
And at those times, we actually are in the experience of anata, the experience of not-self.

163
00:16:52,557 --> 00:16:56,482
Now, it's usually just that we're not reflecting at that time, so therefore we don't...

164
00:16:56,902 --> 00:17:06,730
take it in consciously in a way that we can then talk about to ourselves afterwards and think about because we're just in that lovely direct experience.

165
00:17:07,771 --> 00:17:15,157
But it's worth, if you do have any of those, it's worth just reflecting on them afterwards maybe and just seeing, well, was there much of a sense of self there?

166
00:17:16,358 --> 00:17:26,048
Just to allow this teaching to kind of seep in a bit deeper that it is possible for the sense of self just to fall away and it's happening all the time and causing us no problem at all.

167
00:17:27,057 --> 00:17:28,519
And yet we feel so threatened.

168
00:17:28,558 --> 00:17:31,884
The idea of an atta often is very frightening.

169
00:17:32,503 --> 00:17:35,367
The sense that I don't have any permanent existence.

170
00:17:35,729 --> 00:17:37,270
And it can scare us to think about it.

171
00:17:37,730 --> 00:17:47,344
But I think it's consoling to be told that it's happening all the time and we're just not noticing because it's such a happy, pleasant state.

172
00:17:49,166 --> 00:17:51,390
So we can cope with the truth of an atta.

173
00:17:51,910 --> 00:17:52,510
We can.

174
00:17:52,570 --> 00:17:55,275
Our being is coping with it all the time.

175
00:18:04,097 --> 00:18:17,076
So yeah, the self often means trouble, you know, in the sense that it comes up to fulfil a desire and very often most of our desires are simply reactivity, you know, like reactions to the cold, for example.

176
00:18:17,576 --> 00:18:32,636
We could have been in that very peaceful state of direct experience in walking meditation and then suddenly we just start to feel a bit cold and very quickly then there's crossness and, you know, where's the hat and gloves and

177
00:18:33,358 --> 00:18:40,566
all the self-consciousness maybe about just leaving the walking meditation and wondering will others judge us and they're getting in the way.

178
00:18:40,605 --> 00:18:44,769
So an awful lot of trouble arises with the self very often.

179
00:18:45,330 --> 00:18:49,694
So you can usually tell when the self has arisen by just noting the trouble in life.

180
00:18:52,176 --> 00:18:53,218
It brings a lot of trouble.

181
00:18:54,118 --> 00:18:56,641
My agenda, my needs and so on.

182
00:18:58,583 --> 00:19:02,386
So the sense of self is associated with the stress of reactivity.

183
00:19:02,923 --> 00:19:18,101
And this is really what we mean by Anathaduka, you know, the suffering associated with a self that's trying to control experience, control life, control others in order to be happy.

184
00:19:19,422 --> 00:19:27,230
You know, it's just trying to find happiness, trying to find pleasure, which is very laudable.

185
00:19:27,270 --> 00:19:30,855
I mean, this whole path that we're on is happiness seeking.

186
00:19:31,325 --> 00:19:46,946
But the only trouble with the self trying to find happiness is that it's out of touch with the ultimate reality because the self isn't permanent and basically can't keep manipulating things to keep the happiness for itself.

187
00:19:47,027 --> 00:19:49,490
So it's onto a losing battle immediately.

188
00:19:50,372 --> 00:19:56,760
So it's often associated with deep distress, trying to over-control things.

189
00:19:57,883 --> 00:19:59,424
So I suppose we...

190
00:20:00,518 --> 00:20:03,401
would understand this in terms of over-identification.

191
00:20:03,980 --> 00:20:28,163
Over-identification with our job, where we just get really fussy, things have to be done this way and this way only, and we get maybe perfectionistic, and we won't trust others to help in the work, and we work late, and we work long, and we think ours is the best way and the only way, and then if anyone criticises, of course, it's devastating, and basically the job becomes a torment.

192
00:20:28,295 --> 00:20:32,460
usually for us as well as for others, you know, the over-identification problem.

193
00:20:33,642 --> 00:20:47,799
So it's a lot of distress that, and any area of life where we over-identify with, you know, if we're trying to control family members so that they're the way we think they ought to be, there's an awful lot of unhappiness associated with that.

194
00:20:48,520 --> 00:20:51,805
We can over-identify with anything, a hobby.

195
00:20:53,978 --> 00:21:00,887
We can over-identify, I think, with our spiritual practice and just be stressing ourselves out, trying to get to the state of not-self.

196
00:21:02,450 --> 00:21:05,513
We can do all kinds of things to ourselves.

197
00:21:08,357 --> 00:21:10,520
So it's a tricky area.

198
00:21:10,701 --> 00:21:12,182
It's one to just keep examining.

199
00:21:13,865 --> 00:21:19,594
The distress of this illusion of self that thinks it should be in control.

200
00:21:19,653 --> 00:21:21,296
And then there's an awful lot of self-blame.

201
00:21:21,336 --> 00:21:23,479
You know, when things go wrong, it must be my fault.

202
00:21:24,859 --> 00:21:33,568
because that idea that I can control life means that if things go against me, it was my fault, I didn't control it right.

203
00:21:34,230 --> 00:21:39,776
So a huge amount of self-blame gets embedded in there and very, very, very distressing.

204
00:21:42,558 --> 00:21:47,743
So over-identification would be one way of seeing this anatta dukkha.

205
00:21:51,688 --> 00:21:54,411
But however we can

206
00:21:55,488 --> 00:21:57,769
find the way out, which we're doing here now.

207
00:21:57,829 --> 00:22:02,414
So it's surrendering to the truth that we're actually not in control, not ultimately.

208
00:22:03,016 --> 00:22:07,980
We have a certain level of control, we can decide to meditate, but we can't control our mind state.

209
00:22:08,060 --> 00:22:14,907
We can't make sure that we're concentrated or that we're alert or that we have happy experiences.

210
00:22:16,769 --> 00:22:22,075
So we have only a very limited level of control over our experience.

211
00:22:22,996 --> 00:22:24,718
So it's surrendering to that truth

212
00:22:25,019 --> 00:22:30,426
and knowing that the rotten stuff can happen to anyone, anywhere.

213
00:22:32,170 --> 00:22:33,992
And if it happens to me, it's not my fault.

214
00:22:34,292 --> 00:22:43,547
It's just circumstances coming together so that I'm going through a patch that maybe feels very bad.

215
00:22:44,989 --> 00:22:52,140
But the rotten stuff can be embraced willingly, as we reflect on the truth that there's just no way out of it.

216
00:22:52,491 --> 00:22:55,957
We can't always control and keep away what we don't like.

217
00:22:56,458 --> 00:23:08,517
So therefore the only way to be at peace with the world is to embrace what comes our way as willingly as we possibly can and just trust that this will get deeper and deeper and deeper as we immerse ourselves more deeply in truth.

218
00:23:10,759 --> 00:23:12,643
So it's just exactly the practice here.

219
00:23:12,702 --> 00:23:21,215
Taking an interest in what comes our way, accepting it and

220
00:23:22,259 --> 00:23:26,733
Yes, eventually coming to a deeper peace than we could possibly have as a separate self.

